article.description: Yolanda Griffith had 22 points and nine rebounds to lead the host Sacramento Monarchs to a 65-51 victory Tuesday night over the Indiana Fever.
article.headline: Sacramento assumes top spot in West
article.linkText: Monarchs improve to 6-1 with victory over Fever
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Although they weren't pleased with
their play, the Sacramento Monarchs were glad to get the win.

Yolanda Griffith had 22 points and nine rebounds to lead the
Sacramento Monarchs to a 65-51 victory Tuesday night over the
Indiana Fever.

"It doesn't matter who gets the most points or who gets the
most rebounds for this team, the important thing is to just get the
victory," Griffith said.

Coupled with losses by Houston and Seattle earlier in the night,
the Monarchs (5-1) moved into sole possession of first place in the
Western Conference.

It was the lowest scoring effort of the year for Indiana (4-3),
which has lost two straight and three of four.

Sacramento committed 24 turnovers last week in a 61-60 loss at
Indiana. In the rematch, the Monarchs had just 11 turnovers and
shot 43 percent. The Fever could never get going offensively,
shooting 29 percent (17-for-58).

"When you're not making shots and teams are running it can be
very difficult," Indiana coach Brian Winters said.

The Monarchs led 35-23 at halftime and quickly stretched the
lead to 17 points in the second half. But the Fever staged a
comeback and pulled to within 53-46 with just over 4 minutes
remaining.

Sacramento responded by making 7 of 8 free throws over the next
2 minutes to pull away for its second straight victory.

"When a team gets momentum like that in the end of the game,
they can beat you," Sacramento coach John Whisenant said. "I was
disappointed we let them get back in the game. But they fouled us
and we made our free throws."

Ticha Penicheiro had a season-high 15 points for the Monarchs.
DeMya Walker added 12 points and Nicole Powell scored 10.

It was a difficult evening for Indiana leading scorer Tamika
Catchings, who missed her first nine shots and did not have a field
goal until making a layup with 5:05 remaining in the game. She
finished 2-of-11 shots for 13 points.

"We had a lot of crucial turnovers, you can't do that against a
good team like Sacramento," Catchings said.

Indiana guard Kelly Miller had 12 points before fouling out in
the game's final minutes.

Griffith scored 12 points in the opening half, including five
points during a 12-0 run that gave the Monarchs a 33-18 lead.
